{
  "local_port": 56030,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the best photos of spaceflight?",
  "response": "The best photos of spaceflight often capture the awe-inspiring moments of human exploration, the vastness of space, and the beauty of celestial bodies. Here are some iconic and breathtaking images that stand out in the history of spaceflight:\n\n---\n\n### **1. *Earthrise* (1968)**  \n- **Mission:** Apollo 8  \n- **Description:** Taken by astronaut William Anders, this image shows Earth rising above the lunar horizon. It\u2019s one of the most iconic and humbling photographs ever taken, emphasizing the fragility and beauty of our planet.\n\n---\n\n### **2. *The Blue Marble* (1972)**  \n- **Mission:** Apollo 17  \n- **Description:** This is the first full-view photograph of Earth, capturing the planet in its entirety. It became a symbol of environmental awareness and unity.\n\n---\n\n### **3. *The Pillars of Creation* (1995)**  \n- **Mission:** Hubble Space Telescope  \n- **Description:** This stunning image of the Eagle Nebula, taken by the Hubble Telescope, reveals towering columns of gas and dust where new stars are born. It\u2019s a testament to the beauty of the cosmos.\n\n---\n\n### **4. *First Human on the Moon* (1969)**  \n- **Mission:** Apollo 11  \n- **Description:** Neil Armstrong\u2019s historic first steps on the Moon, captured by Buzz Aldrin\u2019s camera, remain one of the most defining moments in human history.\n\n---\n\n### **5. *Hubble Deep Field* (1995)**  \n- **Mission:** Hubble Space Telescope  \n- **Description:** This image, captured by pointing the Hubble Telescope at a seemingly empty patch of sky, revealed thousands of galaxies, offering a glimpse into the vastness of the universe.\n\n---\n\n### **6. *SpaceX Falcon Heavy Launch* (2018)**  \n- **Mission:** SpaceX Test Flight  \n- **Description:** The launch of SpaceX\u2019s Falcon Heavy rocket was accompanied by a surreal image of Elon Musk\u2019s Tesla Roadster drifting through space with Earth in the background.\n\n---\n\n### **7. *International Space Station Over Earth***  \n- **Mission:** Various ISS Expeditions  \n- **Description:** Photos of the ISS orbiting Earth, often with the auroras or city lights below, highlight humanity\u2019s presence in space and the engineering marvel of the station.\n\n---\n\n### **8. *Pluto\u2019s Heart* (2015)**  \n- **Mission:** New Horizons  \n- **Description:** This close-up of Pluto, with its heart-shaped feature on the surface, revealed the dwarf planet in unprecedented detail and captured the public\u2019s imagination.\n\n---\n\n### **9. *Astronaut Spacewalk* (1984)**  \n- **Mission:** STS-41-B (Space Shuttle Challenger)  \n- **Description:** Bruce McCandless II became the first astronaut to perform an untethered spacewalk, captured in an image of him floating freely in space.\n\n---\n\n### **10. *Jupiter\u2019s Great Red Spot* (2017)**  \n- **Mission:** Juno  \n- **Description:** NASA\u2019s Juno spacecraft captured incredible close-ups of Jupiter\u2019s iconic storm, showcasing the planet\u2019s turbulent atmosphere.\n\n---\n\n### Honorable Mentions:  \n- **The Pale Blue Dot (1990):** Taken by Voyager 1, this image shows Earth as a tiny speck in the vastness of space.  \n- **Curiosity Rover\u2019s Selfie (2020):** Mars\u2019 surface with the rover in the foreground, showcasing humanity\u2019s exploration of the Red Planet.  \n- **Auroras from the ISS:** Stunning images of Earth\u2019s auroras as seen from space.\n\n---\n\nThese photos not only document the history of space exploration but also inspire wonder and curiosity about the universe. They remind us of the incredible achievements of science, technology, and human ingenuity.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
